# üñ•Ô∏è Basic Example of C# Code

Below is a **simple console-based calculator in C#**.  
It demonstrates:
- Taking user input
- Converting input types
- Using `switch` statements for basic operations

---

## üìå Code Example

```csharp
using System;  
namespace HelloWorld  
{  
    class Program  
    {  
        static void Main(string[] args)  
        {  
            Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");  
          
            // Read first number   
            Console.Write("Enter Number 1: ");  
            var var1 = Console.ReadLine();  
            int num1 = Convert.ToInt32(var1);  
  
            // Read second number  
            Console.Write("Enter Number 2: ");  
            var var2 = Console.ReadLine();  
            int num2 = Convert.ToInt32(var2);  
  
            // Read operation type - operator  
            Console.Write("Enter one Operator (Add/Sub/Mul/Div): ");              
            var op = Console.ReadLine();                    
              
            switch (op)  
            {  
                case "Add":  
                    Console.WriteLine("Add {0}:", num1 + num2);  
                    break;  
                case "Sub":  
                    Console.WriteLine("Sub {0}:", num1 - num2);  
                    break;  
                case "Mul":  
                    double result = num1 * num2;  
                    Console.WriteLine("Mul {0}:", result);  
                    break;  
                case "Div":  
                    double res = (double)num1 / num2;  
                    Console.WriteLine("Div {0}:", res);  
                    break;  
                default:  
                    Console.WriteLine("Operation failed!");  
                    break;  
            }  
              
            Console.WriteLine("Press any key to exit...");  
            Console.ReadKey(true);              
        }  
    }  
}  
